 "publication": {
  "pmid": "16600963",
  "doi": "10.1110/ps.051936406",
  "title": "Directed evolution of human T cell receptor CDR2 residues by phage display dramatically enhances affinity for cognate peptide-MHC without increasing apparent cross-reactivity.",
  "journal": "Protein science : a publication of the Protein Society",
  "year": 2006,
  "authors": "Dunn SM, Rizkallah PJ, Baston E, Mahon T, Cameron B, Moysey R, Gao F, Sami M, Boulter J, Li Y, Jakobsen BK."
 },
 "executive_summary": "This study engineered the CDR2 regions of a human T cell receptor through phage display to dramatically enhance binding affinity for a cognate peptide-MHC complex while maintaining specificity\u2014a counterintuitive result, since CDR2 loops typically contact only the MHC surface rather than the peptide itself. The engineered low-nanomolar-affinity TCRs retained high specificity for their target pMHC, with structural analysis revealing that improved shape complementarity at the CDR2-MHC contact interface drove the affinity gain. This finding challenges the expectation that increasing TCR affinity would necessarily increase off-target cross-reactivity, suggesting instead that careful mutagenesis of germline-encoded CDR2 loops can improve binding without sacrificing recognition selectivity. The work has direct implications for TCR engineering approaches in therapeutic and diagnostic applications, indicating that the MHC-contact surface\u2014not just peptide-contact regions\u2014offers a tractable avenue for generating high-affinity, specific TCRs suitable for clinical use.",
